1	\chapter{Genus of a smooth proper curve}
2	\label{chap:Genus}
3	
4	Throughout this chapter, $k$ denotes a field and $C$ a smooth proper geometrically irreducible scheme over $k$ of relative dimension $1$ — that is, $C \to \Spec k$ carries the typeclasses
5	\lstinline{[SmoothOfRelativeDimension 1 C.hom] [IsProper C.hom] [GeometricallyIrreducible C.hom]}.
6	We call such a $C$ a \emph{smooth proper curve over $k$}.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}[Genus of a smooth proper curve]
11	  \label{def:genus}
12	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.genus}
13	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
14	  The \emph{genus} of a smooth proper curve $C$ over $k$ is the natural number
15	  \[
16	    g(C) \;=\; \dim_k H^1(C,\, \mathcal O_C),
17	  \]
18	  the $k$-dimension of the first sheaf-cohomology group of the structure sheaf of $C$.
19	\end{definition}
20	
21	\begin{proof}
22	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
23	  The Lean implementation expresses this via the project's $\ModuleCat\,k$-flavoured sheaf cohomology of the structure sheaf:
24	  \[
25	    \mathtt{genus}\,C \;:=\; \Module.\mathtt{finrank}\,k\,\bigl(\Scheme.\HModule\,k\,(\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1\bigr).
26	  \]
27	  The carrier $\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C$ is the iter-006 sheaf-of-$k$-modules constructed from $\struct C$ via the structure morphism $C.\mathrm{hom}$; the wrapper $\Scheme.\HModule\,k\,F\,1$ is the iter-009 $\Module\,k$-flavoured sheaf cohomology, given by $\Ext_{\Sheaf(\opens C, \ModuleCat\,k)}((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k),\, F,\, 1)$, which carries a canonical $\Module\,k$-structure inherited from \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.instModule} (against the $\Linear\,k$-enrichment of $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$, auto-inferable from \lstinline{HasSheafify}).
28	
29	  Mathlib's $\Module.\mathtt{finrank}$ returns the $k$-dimension when the underlying module is finite-dimensional and zero otherwise. For a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve, Serre's theorem on coherent cohomology of a proper $k$-scheme guarantees $\dim_k H^1(C, \struct C) < \infty$, so $g(C)$ is the geometric genus on the relevant case (Serre finiteness is left as Phase A step 6 *proper* and is not invoked at the level of the *definition*). The closure is therefore the one-liner
30	  \[
31	    \Module.\mathtt{finrank}\,k\,\bigl(\Scheme.\HModule\,k\,(\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1\bigr),
32	  \]
33	  probe-confirmed to typecheck against current Mathlib (kernel-only axioms) in the iter-011 plan-agent's \lstinline{lean_run_code} probe.
34	\end{proof}
35	
36	Equivalent reformulations available once Riemann–Roch and Serre duality are formalised:
37	\begin{itemize}
38	  \item $g(C) = \dim_k H^0(C,\, \Omega^1_{C/k})$ (Serre duality).
39	  \item $g(C) = 1 - \chi(\mathcal O_C)$, where $\chi$ is the Euler characteristic.
40	  \item For a smooth projective curve over $\mathbb C$, $g(C)$ equals the topological genus of $C(\mathbb C)$.
41	\end{itemize}
42	Each of these requires Mathlib infrastructure that is currently absent. The first reformulation in particular requires the sheaf of relative differentials of schemes (Phase B of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}), and the others require Riemann–Roch / Serre duality / a topological-vs-algebraic geometry comparison (out of project scope for the foreseeable iterations).
43	
44	\section{Mathlib gap}
45	\label{sec:Genus_status}
46	
47	The honest definition $\dim_k H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$ requires a $\Module\,k$-flavoured sheaf cohomology of $\struct C$ on the topology of opens of $C.\mathrm{left}$. Through iter-010 the project has built this:
48	
49	\begin{itemize}
50	  \item \textbf{Sheaf cohomology of $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheaves} (\lstinline{CategoryTheory.Sheaf.H}, file \lstinline{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/Basic.lean}, Mathlib): defined as $\Ext$ from the constant sheaf at $\AddCommGrpCat.\mathrm{of}\,(\ULift\,\mathbb Z)$.
51	  \item \textbf{Sheaf cohomology of $\ModuleCat\,k$-valued sheaves} (\lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule}, this project, iter-009): the parallel $\Module\,k$-valued construction with unit object $\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k$ instead of $\ULift\,\mathbb Z$, gluing through the $\Linear\,k$-enrichment of $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$ to recover a $\Module\,k$ structure on the cohomology groups.
52	  \item \textbf{Structure sheaf as a $\ModuleCat\,k$-valued sheaf} (\lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf}, this project, iter-006): for $C : \mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$, the sheafification of the presheaf $U \mapsto \ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,(\Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, U))$ where the $k$-action is the algebra structure induced by the structure morphism $C.\mathrm{hom}$.
53	  \item \textbf{$H^0$ algebraic bridge} (\lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule_zero_linearEquiv}, this project, iter-010): $H^0(C, \struct C)_{\Module\,k} \simeq_k \Hom_{\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)}((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\dots).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k),\, \toModuleKSheaf\,C)$, via Mathlib's \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀}. Used downstream for the geometric content $H^0(C, \struct C) \simeq k$ on a connected proper $k$-curve (multi-iteration; iter-012+).
54	\end{itemize}
55	
56	The remaining Mathlib gap for the *theorem* (as opposed to the *definition*) of genus:
57	
58	\begin{itemize}
59	  \item \textbf{Serre finiteness for $H^i(C, \mathcal F)$ on a proper $k$-curve} (\lstinline{Module.Finite k (HModule k (toModuleKSheaf C) i)} in our setting). Mathlib's \lstinline{ModuleCat.finite_ext} (\lstinline{Mathlib/Algebra/Category/ModuleCat/Ext/Finite.lean}) provides $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}$ for module-Ext only, not sheaf-Ext. Path 2 (Čech-cohomology scaffold; Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.cechComplexFunctor} is now available) is the recommended iter-012+ direction.
60	\end{itemize}
61	
62	\section{User authorisation of \texttt{noncomputable}}
63	\label{sec:Genus_noncomputable}
64	
65	The original \lstinline{references/challenge.lean} writes \lstinline{def genus}, not \lstinline{noncomputable def genus}. Because \lstinline{Module.finrank}, \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.instModule}, and the structure-sheaf-as-$k$-module construction are all noncomputable in Mathlib, the honest closure of the body requires the \lstinline{noncomputable} modifier on the \lstinline{def}. The user (\texttt{2026-05-07}) explicitly authorised agents to add this modifier as a "non-signature change": names, argument types, and argument order remain verbatim. The iter-011 refactor agent therefore changes \lstinline{def genus} to \lstinline{noncomputable def genus} (and imports \lstinline{AlgebraicJacobian.Cohomology.StructureSheafModuleK}); the iter-011 prover round fills the body.
66	
67	\section{What \emph{this} iteration does and does not}
68	
69	This (iter-011) iteration *defines* the genus. It does not *compute* it on any specific curve, and it does not prove that the result equals the geometric genus in the classical sense (which requires Serre finiteness for non-vacuity and Riemann–Roch for verification on examples). The downstream theorem \lstinline{smoothOfRelativeDimension_genus} in \lstinline{Jacobian.lean} states $\Jacobian C$ is smooth of relative dimension $\genus C$ — that theorem will require Serre finiteness on the way (because \lstinline{Jacobian C} is a $g(C)$-dimensional scheme) and is queued for the iteration that closes \lstinline{Jacobian C} itself, which is gated on Phase C representability and is multi-iteration upstream work.
70

1	\chapter{The Jacobian as an abelian variety}
2	\label{chap:Jacobian}
3	
4	Let $C$ be a smooth proper curve over $k$ in the sense of Chapter~\ref{chap:Genus}, with genus $g = g(C)$.
5	
6	Because the Picard-scheme machinery (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}) is blocked at the level of \lstinline{MonoidalCategory X.Modules} and the full FGA representability theorem, this chapter builds the Jacobian by an alternative ad-hoc route: the Albanese functor on smooth proper curves.
7	
8	\section{The Albanese construction}
9	
10	For a smooth proper curve $C$ over $k$, the Albanese variety is the universal abelian variety receiving a morphism from $C$.  Over an algebraically closed field this is classically identified with the connected component of the identity of the Picard scheme, but we construct it directly from symmetric powers.
11	
12	\subsection{Symmetric powers and the Abel--Jacobi map}
13	
14	Let $C^{(g)} = \operatorname{Sym}^g(C)$ be the $g$\textsuperscript{th} symmetric power of $C$ (the quotient of $C^g$ by the action of the symmetric group $S_g$).  It is a smooth proper scheme over $k$ of dimension $g$.  Fix a $k$-rational point $P_0 \in C(k)$.  The map
15	\[
16	  \sigma \colon C^{(g)} \longrightarrow \Pic^g_{C/k}, \qquad
17	  \sum_{i=1}^g [P_i] \longmapsto \mathcal O_C\bigl(\textstyle\sum_{i=1}^g P_i - g P_0\bigr)
18	\]
19	is surjective and birational onto its image; its fibres are projective spaces (Brill--Noether--Riemann--Roch).  Choosing $P_0$ gives a translation isomorphism $\Pic^g_{C/k} \xrightarrow{\;\sim\;} \Pic^0_{C/k}$, and the Stein factorisation of $\sigma$ yields the Jacobian as the connected component of the identity.
20	
21	In the Lean formalisation we do not have general symmetric powers of schemes (or quotients by finite group actions) in Mathlib.  We therefore take a more direct approach: we define the Jacobian as the Albanese object of $C$ inside the category of smooth proper group schemes over $k$, using the universal property and the known dimension formula.
22	
23	\begin{definition}[Jacobian]
24	  \label{def:Jacobian}
25	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian}
26	  \uses{def:genus}
27	  The \emph{Jacobian} of $C$ is the abelian variety $\Jac(C)$ over $k$ obtained as the Albanese object of $C$: a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $k$ of dimension $g(C)$ equipped with a universal morphism $C \to \Jac(C)$.  It is viewed as an object of $\textrm{Over}(\Spec k)$.
28	\end{definition}
29	
30	\section{Group scheme structure and abelian-variety properties}
31	
32	\begin{theorem}[Group object structure]
33	  \label{thm:Jacobian_grpObj}
34	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.instGrpObj}
35	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
36	  $\Jac(C)$ carries a canonical group-object structure in $\textrm{Over}(\Spec k)$, induced by the Albanese universal property and the cogroup structure of $C$ in the category of pointed curves.
37	\end{theorem}
38	
39	\begin{theorem}[Smoothness and dimension]
40	  \label{thm:Jacobian_smooth_genus}
41	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.smoothOfRelativeDimension_genus}
42	  \uses{def:Jacobian, def:genus}
43	  $\Jac(C) \to \Spec k$ is smooth of relative dimension $g(C)$.
44	\end{theorem}
45	
46	\begin{theorem}[Properness]
47	  \label{thm:Jacobian_proper}
48	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.instIsProper}
49	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
50	  $\Jac(C) \to \Spec k$ is proper.
51	\end{theorem}
52	
53	\begin{theorem}[Geometric irreducibility]
54	  \label{thm:Jacobian_geomIrred}
55	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.instGeometricallyIrreducible}
56	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
57	  $\Jac(C) \to \Spec k$ is geometrically irreducible.
58	\end{theorem}
59	
60	\noindent All four properties are part of the Albanese construction.  Smoothness and dimension follow from the deformation-theoretic identification of the tangent space at the identity with $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$ (Phase~A, Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafAb}).  Properness and geometric irreducibility descend from the corresponding properties of $C$ because the Albanese map is surjective with connected fibres.
61	
62	\subsection{Sanity check in low genus}
63	
64	\begin{itemize}
65	  \item $g = 0$: Then $\Jac(C) = \Spec k$, the trivial group scheme; $\Jac(\mathbb P^1_k) = \Spec k$ is smooth of relative dimension $0 = g$.  The terminal object of $\textrm{Over}(\Spec k)$ already carries \lstinline{GrpObj} via \lstinline{instTensorUnit}.
66	  \item $g = 1$: Then $\Jac(C) \cong C$ once a $k$-rational point on $C$ is fixed; $C$ is itself an abelian variety.
67	  \item $g \ge 2$: $\Jac(C)$ is a non-trivial $g$-dimensional abelian variety, never isomorphic to $C$ as a scheme.
68	\end{itemize}
69	
70	\section{Implementation route in Lean}
71	
72	Because the full Picard-scheme representability theorem is not available in Mathlib, the formal construction proceeds in two layers:
73	
74	\begin{enumerate}
75	  \item \textbf{Layer I -- direct definition.}  Define \lstinline{Jacobian C} as an object of \lstinline{Over (Spec (.of k))} carrying the four instances above.  In the first instance the underlying scheme can be taken to be the terminal object \lstinline{⊤_ (Over (Spec (.of k)))} when the genus is $0$, and for higher genus it is built from an ad-hoc quotient of a suitable symmetric-power-like functor.  Since Mathlib lacks general quotients of schemes by finite group actions, we instead rely on the Albanese universal property: \lstinline{Jacobian C} is declared as the representing object of the Albanese functor for $C$.
76	
77	  \item \textbf{Layer II -- Abel--Jacobi compatibility.}  Chapter~\ref{chap:AbelJacobi} introduces the Abel--Jacobi morphism $C \to \Jac(C)$ and shows that it is universal among morphisms from $C$ to abelian varieties.  This is the content of the three protected sorries in \lstinline{AbelJacobi.lean}.
78	\end{enumerate}
79	
80	\noindent The five protected sorries in \lstinline{Jacobian.lean} (\lstinline{Jacobian}, \lstinline{instGrpObj}, \lstinline{smoothOfRelativeDimension_genus}, \lstinline{instIsProper}, \lstinline{instGeometricallyIrreducible}) and the three in \lstinline{AbelJacobi.lean} (\lstinline{ofCurve}, \lstinline{comp_ofCurve}, \lstinline{exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}) are now in active scope for the prover.  They are assigned to the Phase~C parallel track of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}.
81

1	\chapter{Sheaf condition along the structure-sheaf forget composite}
2	\label{chap:Cohomology_SheafCompose}
3	
4	This chapter records the first step of Phase A in \texttt{STRATEGY.md}: equipping the abstract Mathlib sheaf-cohomology pipeline with the link it needs to compute $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$ as an abelian group. It is the smallest unblocking unit of progress toward Definition~\ref{def:genus} (the genus of a smooth proper curve).
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$ in subsequent Phase A iterations.
7	
8	\section{Statement}
9	
10	Mathlib has the abstract Grothendieck-topology sheaf-cohomology API
11	\lstinline{CategoryTheory.Sheaf.H : Sheaf J AddCommGrpCat → ℕ → Type w'}, but the structure sheaf $\mathcal O_C$ of a scheme is delivered by Mathlib in the shape \lstinline{TopCat.Sheaf CommRingCat C} (i.e.\ $\mathrm{CommRing}$-valued, not $\mathrm{Ab}$-valued). To plug $\mathcal O_C$ into the cohomology API we must first transport the sheaf condition along the forgetful composite $\mathrm{CommRing} \to \mathrm{Ring} \to \mathrm{Ab}$. The \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} typeclass packages exactly this transport.
12	
13	\begin{theorem}[Sheaf condition transports along the structure-sheaf forget composite]
14	  \label{thm:HasSheafCompose_forget}
15	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Cohomology.instHasSheafCompose_forget_CommRing_AddCommGrp}
16	  Let $X$ be a topological space. Then the Grothendieck topology of opens of $X$ has
17	  \[
18	    \mathtt{HasSheafCompose}\bigl(
19	      \mathrm{forget}_2\, \mathrm{CommRingCat}\, \mathrm{RingCat} \;\circ\;
20	      \mathrm{forget}_2\, \mathrm{RingCat}\, \mathrm{AddCommGrpCat}
21	    \bigr).
22	  \]
23	\end{theorem}
24	
25	In Lean:
26	\begin{lstlisting}
27	instance (X : TopCat) :
28	    (TopologicalSpace.Opens.grothendieckTopology X).HasSheafCompose
29	      (CategoryTheory.forget₂ CommRingCat RingCat ⋙
30	       CategoryTheory.forget₂ RingCat AddCommGrpCat)
31	\end{lstlisting}
32	
33	\section{Proof sketch}
34	
35	\begin{proof}
36	  Both $\mathrm{forget}_2 \mathrm{CommRingCat}\, \mathrm{RingCat}$ and $\mathrm{forget}_2 \mathrm{RingCat}\, \mathrm{AddCommGrpCat}$ are algebraic structure-forgetful functors and hence \emph{create} (in particular preserve) all small limits. The sheaf condition for the topology of opens is expressed as preservation of certain limits of the form \lstinline{multiequalizer (Cover.index ...)} (see \lstinline{Presheaf.IsSheaf.isSheaf_iff_isSheaf_of_type} and the multispan-limit reformulation \lstinline{IsSheaf.isLimit_multifork}). Composing two limit-preserving functors gives a limit-preserving functor, so the post-composition with the forget composite preserves the sheaf condition. The \lstinline{HasSheafCompose} typeclass is exactly the resulting "sheaf-of-rings becomes sheaf-of-abelian-groups" lemma.
37	\end{proof}
38	
39	\section{Use in the project}
40	
41	Theorem~\ref{thm:HasSheafCompose_forget} is the gateway to:
42	
43	\begin{itemize}
44	  \item the construction of $\mathcal O_C$ as a sheaf of abelian groups on $C$, by post-composing $\mathcal O_C : \mathrm{Opens}(C)^{\mathrm{op}} \to \mathrm{CommRingCat}$ with the forget composite — the resulting object lives in $\mathrm{Sheaf}(\mathrm{Opens.gT}\, C, \mathrm{AddCommGrpCat})$ thanks to the typeclass above;
45	  \item plugging that sheaf into \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Sheaf.H} once \lstinline{HasSheafify (Opens.gT C) AddCommGrpCat} and \lstinline{HasExt} are available (Phase A steps 2--3);
46	  \item endowing the resulting $H^1$ with a $k$-vector-space structure via the $k$-algebra structure on $\Gamma(C, \mathcal O_C)$ (Phase A step 4);
47	  \item finite-dimensionality via Serre's theorem on coherent cohomology of proper $k$-schemes (Phase A step 5);
48	  \item Definition~\ref{def:genus} ($g(C) = \dim_k H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$) which then becomes formalisable.
49	\end{itemize}
50	
51	The chain is: \texttt{HasSheafCompose} (this chapter) $\to$ \texttt{HasSheafify} $\to$ \texttt{HasExt} $\to$ $\mathrm{Module}\, k$-on-$H^1$ $\to$ Serre finiteness $\to$ \lstinline{genus}.
52	
53	\section{Mathlib gap}
54	
55	Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} has all the constituent pieces:
56	\begin{itemize}
57	  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.GrothendieckTopology.HasSheafCompose} — the typeclass to populate.
58	  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasForget₂} for $\mathrm{CommRingCat} \to \mathrm{RingCat}$ (\lstinline{CommRingCat.hasForgetToRingCat}) and $\mathrm{RingCat} \to \mathrm{AddCommGrpCat}$ (\lstinline{RingCat.hasForgetToAddCommGrp}).
59	  \item Limit-preservation lemmas for algebraic forgetful functors and the sheaf-condition reformulations.
