303	\begin{remark}[What iter-012 does and does not do]
304	  Iter-012 \emph{defines} the Čech cochain complex and Čech cohomology object of the structure sheaf for an arbitrary indexed open cover. Iter-012 does \emph{not} prove that this Čech cohomology agrees with the derived-functor cohomology $\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf C)\,n$ of Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule} — the comparison theorem requires the cover to be \emph{acyclic} (e.g., all opens affine, plus Serre's vanishing on affine schemes for quasi-coherent sheaves), neither of which is iter-012 work. The comparison theorem is queued for iter-013+; the affine-finiteness step (each cochain group is finite-dimensional over $k$ when the cover is affine and the curve is proper) is queued for iter-014+; the dimension-vanishing step (degree $> 1$ vanishes on a curve) is queued for iter-015+.
305	\end{remark}
306	
307	\begin{remark}[Why two declarations and not one]
308	  Splitting $\check C^\bullet$ from $\check H^n$ matches Mathlib's standard pattern (\lstinline{cechComplexFunctor} returns a complex; \lstinline{HomologicalComplex.homology} extracts a degree). The complex is useful in its own right (e.g., for explicit cocycle / coboundary calculations, or for showing exactness on a specific cover), so we expose it as a separate API surface.
309	\end{remark}
