628	\end{lemma}
629	
630	\subsection{Use in Serre finiteness}
631	
632	For a proper geometrically integral $k$-curve $C$ a $2$-affine cover with affine intersection always exists (e.g.\ remove a closed point to get one affine, remove another to get the second; their intersection is the curve minus two points, again affine on a $k$-curve). The bundle $C.\AffineCoverMVSquare$ then feeds the iter-029+ Serre-finiteness chain:
633	\begin{enumerate}
634	  \item The MV-LES applied to $S.\toMayerVietorisSquare$ and $\toModuleKSheaf\,C$ gives a $5$-term sequence relating $H^0$ and $H^1$ of $X = \top$, $U_1$, $U_2$, $U_1 \cap U_2$.
635	  \item The cover hypothesis $S.\cover \,\colon\, U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$ identifies the $X_4$ piece with $\top$ (i.e.\ all of $C$).
636	  \item The affineness of $U_1$, $U_2$, $U_1 \cap U_2$ collapses $H^{>0}$ on those pieces (Serre vanishing on affines), reducing the LES to a $3$-term sequence relating $H^0(C, \mathcal O_C)$, $H^0(U_j, \mathcal O)$ and $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$.
637	  \item Each $H^0$ piece is a $k$-module given by a finite ring computation, hence finite-dimensional, hence so is $H^1$.
638	\end{enumerate}
639	Step 4 is the actual Serre finiteness; iter-028 lands only the bundle structure $\AffineCoverMVSquare$ and the abstract-MV-square accessor $\toMayerVietorisSquare$. Iter-029 (next) lands the four corner-identification $\mathtt{simp}$ lemmas that drive Step 2 plus the abstract-LES specialisation that drives Step 1. The remaining steps (Step 3 + Step 4) are iter-030+ work.
