580	\label{sec:scheme_affineCoverMVSquare}
581	
582	After iter-027's file split the abstract Mayer-Vietoris LES on $\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$ is complete and self-contained in this chapter. The next step toward Serre finiteness on a proper $k$-curve is to provide a \emph{specialisation} of the abstract LES to the geometric setting in which Serre finiteness is actually proved: a quasi-compact separated $k$-scheme $X$ admitting an open cover by two affines $U_1, U_2$ whose intersection $U_1 \cap U_2$ is again affine.
583	
584	\subsection{Why this is the natural iter-028 target}
585	
586	Serre's finiteness theorem on a proper $k$-curve is proved by Čech-cohomology computation on a 2-affine cover: the sheaf cohomology $H^i(X, \mathcal F)$ vanishes for $i \geq 2$ (because the cover has only two pieces and the Čech complex is concentrated in degrees $0, 1$), and is finite-dimensional over $k$ in degrees $0$ and $1$ because each $\mathcal F(U_j)$ is a finitely generated module over the affine ring of $U_j$ and the cohomology is a sub/quotient of finite-dimensional pieces. The Mayer-Vietoris LES we built in iter-014 $\to$ iter-026 is the categorical engine that lets us extract these vanishing/finiteness facts \emph{abstractly} from the affine vanishing $H^{>0}(\Spec A, \mathcal F) = 0$ — but to use it on $X$ rather than on $U_1 \sqcup U_2$, we need a Mayer-Vietoris square whose total piece $X_4$ is $X$ itself, not just $U_1 \sqcup U_2$. The total-cover hypothesis $U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$ is therefore load-bearing.
587	
588	Mathlib provides $\Opens.\mayerVietorisSquare \,\colon\, \Opens\,T \to \Opens\,T \to (\Opens.\grothendieckTopology\,T).\MayerVietorisSquare$ (\texttt{Mathlib/Topology/Sheaves/MayerVietoris.lean}), which produces an abstract square with $X_1 = U_1 \sqcap U_2$, $X_2 = U_1$, $X_3 = U_2$, $X_4 = U_1 \sqcup U_2$, but does \emph{not} record the affineness of any of these pieces and does \emph{not} express that $U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$ when that is the case. The iter-028 scaffold target therefore packages the four affineness conditions ($\IsAffineOpen\,U_1$, $\IsAffineOpen\,U_2$, $\IsAffineOpen\,(U_1 \sqcap U_2)$) plus the cover hypothesis ($U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$) into a bundled structure $\AffineCoverMVSquare\,X$ on a single scheme $X$, and exposes the underlying Mathlib MV square as an accessor. Downstream Serre-finiteness work can then unpack the structure into (a) Čech-/MV-LES inputs and (b) affine-vanishing inputs.
589	
590	\subsection{Mathlib gap and design}
591	
592	There is no $\AffineCoverMVSquare$ analog in Mathlib; the abstract $\MayerVietorisSquare$ exists for any preordered category with a Grothendieck topology, but the affineness conditions (which are scheme-specific) are not in scope at that level. The iter-028 scaffold introduces the bundled scheme-flavored structure, with the four corner accessors definitionally equal to $U_1 \sqcap U_2$, $U_1$, $U_2$, $U_1 \sqcup U_2$ via the Mathlib $\Opens.\mayerVietorisSquare$ constructor (probe-confirmed $\rfl$, see Lemma~\ref{lem:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_corners}). The cover hypothesis $\cover \,\colon\, U_1 \sqcup U_2 = \top$ is recorded but not consumed by $\toMayerVietorisSquare$; iter-029+ Serre-finiteness lemmas will use it to identify $X_4$ with $\top$ and hence read off cohomology of the whole scheme $X$.
