1312	\subsection{Čech acyclicity for the structure sheaf on affine basic-open covers}
1313	\label{sec:basicOpenCover_isCechAcyclicCover_toModuleKSheaf}
1314	
1315	Let $C$ be a $k$-scheme, $U \subseteq C$ an affine open, and $s \subseteq \mathcal O_C(U)$ a finite generating set for the unit ideal of $\mathcal O_C(U)$. Denote by $D(f) \subseteq U$ the basic open associated with $f \in \mathcal O_C(U)$, and write $\mathfrak U = \{D(f)\}_{f \in s}$ for the basic-open cover of $U$ indexed by $s$. The Čech cochain complex of the structure sheaf $\mathcal O_C$ with respect to this cover is
1316	\[
1317	  C^n(\mathfrak U, \mathcal O_C) \;=\; \prod_{(f_0, \ldots, f_n) \in s^{n+1}} \mathcal O_C\!\left(D(f_0) \cap \cdots \cap D(f_n)\right),
1318	\]
1319	with the standard alternating-coface differential $\delta^n = \sum_{j=0}^{n+1} (-1)^j \delta_j$.
1320	
1321	\begin{theorem}
1322	
1323	  [Čech acyclicity for the structure sheaf on basic-open covers]
1324	  \label{thm:basicOpenCover_isCechAcyclicCover_toModuleKSheaf}
1325	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_isCechAcyclicCover_toModuleKSheaf}
1326	  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover, def:Scheme_IsCechAcyclicCover, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_eq_basicOpen_prod, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_le, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_isLocalization}
1327	  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a $k$-scheme, $U \subseteq C$ an affine open, and $s \subseteq \mathcal O_C(U)$ a subset such that the ideal generated by $s$ in $\mathcal O_C(U)$ is the unit ideal. Then the Čech cochain complex of the structure sheaf with respect to the basic-open cover $\mathfrak U = \{D(f)\}_{f \in s}$ of $U$ is acyclic in positive degrees: for every $n \ge 1$,
1328	  \[
1329	    \check H^n\!\left(\mathfrak U,\, \mathcal O_C\right) \;=\; 0.
1330	  \]
1331	\end{theorem}
1332	
1333	\begin{proof}
1334	  \uses{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_isLocalization, def:Scheme_IsCechAcyclicCover}
1335	  This is the classical Čech-acyclicity theorem for affine schemes (Hartshorne, \emph{Algebraic Geometry}, III.3.5; Stacks Project, tag 01ED). The proof has four steps.
1336	
1337	  \textbf{Step 1: Reduction to per-generator local exactness.}
1338	  Acyclicity of $C^\bullet(\mathfrak U, \mathcal O_C)$ in positive degrees amounts to exactness of the differential $\delta^n$ at each $n \ge 1$. Since $s$ generates the unit ideal of $\mathcal O_C(U)$, exactness of an $\mathcal O_C(U)$-linear map is a local property at the cover $\{\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathcal O_C(U)[1/f]\}_{f \in s}$ of $\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathcal O_C(U)$: an exact sequence of $\mathcal O_C(U)$-modules is exact if and only if it remains exact after localizing at each $f \in s$. We therefore fix $f \in s$ and reduce to showing exactness of the localized differential $\delta^n[1/f]$.
1339	
1340	  \textbf{Step 2: Identification of the localized Čech complex.}
1341	  Localizing the Čech complex at $f$ produces a chain of $\mathcal O_C(U)[1/f]$-modules. The factor at multi-index $(f_0, \ldots, f_n) \in s^{n+1}$ is $\mathcal O_C(D(f_0) \cap \cdots \cap D(f_n))[1/f]$. The intersection $D(f_0) \cap \cdots \cap D(f_n)$ equals $D(f_0 \cdots f_n)$ in $C$ (because basic opens form a sub-multiplicative system); applied to $U$ basic-open by $f$ this becomes $D(f \cdot f_0 \cdots f_n) \subseteq U$. By the standard identification of structure-sheaf sections on a basic open with a localization,
1342	  \[
1343	    \mathcal O_C\!\left(D(f_0) \cap \cdots \cap D(f_n)\right)[1/f] \;\cong\; \mathcal O_C(U)[1/(f \cdot f_0 \cdots f_n)],
1344	  \]
1345	  where the isomorphism is induced by the universal property of localization. Reassembling the products, the localized Čech complex $C^\bullet(\mathfrak U, \mathcal O_C)[1/f]$ is naturally isomorphic to the Čech complex of the structure sheaf of $D(f)$ with respect to the cover $\{D(f) \cap D(f')\}_{f' \in s}$ of $D(f)$.
1346	
1347	  \textbf{Step 3: The $D(f)$-local Čech complex contracts.}
1348	  Inside the cover $\{D(f) \cap D(f')\}_{f' \in s}$ of $D(f)$, the member at $f' = f$ is $D(f) \cap D(f) = D(f)$ itself, the entire ambient affine. The augmentation $\mathcal O_C(D(f)) \to C^0$ sending $a$ to the constant family $(a)_{f'} \in \prod_{f'} \mathcal O_C(D(f) \cap D(f'))$ therefore admits a section: the map sending $(a_{f'})_{f' \in s}$ to its $f' = f$ component. This section, suitably extended in higher degrees, exhibits an \emph{extra degeneracy} on the augmented Čech simplicial object — the standard contraction-by-vertex construction (see e.g.\ Stacks Project, tag 09CN, or Weibel, \emph{An Introduction to Homological Algebra}, §8.6). By the general homotopical fact that an augmented simplicial object equipped with an extra degeneracy is contractible, the augmented Čech complex over $D(f)$ is null-homotopic; in particular it is exact in all positive degrees, and the augmentation $\mathcal O_C(D(f)) \to C^0$ is an isomorphism onto $\ker \delta^0$.
1349	
1350	  \textbf{Step 4: Globalization.}
1351	  Each localized differential $\delta^n[1/f]$ is therefore exact for every $f \in s$, so by the local-to-global principle for spanning sets the unlocalized $\delta^n$ is also exact, proving $\check H^n(\mathfrak U, \mathcal O_C) = 0$ for $n \ge 1$.
1352	\end{proof}
1353	
1354	\textbf{Mathlib leverage.} Step~1 uses the local-to-global theorem for spanning sets (\texttt{exact\_of\_isLocalized\_span} or \texttt{exact\_of\_localized\_span} in \texttt{Mathlib/RingTheory/LocalProperties/Exactness.lean}). Step~2 uses the structure-sheaf-section-as-localization theorem for affine basic opens (\texttt{IsAffineOpen.isLocalization\_of\_eq\_basicOpen} in \texttt{Mathlib/AlgebraicGeometry/AffineScheme.lean}), already packaged for the project's $n$-ary intersection by Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_isLocalization}, plus exactness preservation under localization (\texttt{IsLocalizedModule.map\_exact} in \texttt{Mathlib/Algebra/Module/LocalizedModule/Exact.lean}). Step~3 uses the extra-degeneracy contraction theorem (\texttt{ExtraDegeneracy.homotopyEquiv} in \texttt{Mathlib/AlgebraicTopology/ExtraDegeneracy.lean}) packaged for Čech objects (\texttt{FormalCoproduct.extraDegeneracyCech} in \texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Limits/FormalCoproducts/ExtraDegeneracy.lean}). Mathlib's extra-degeneracy is set up on augmented simplicial objects valued in chain complexes; the project's Čech complex, built on the cosimplicial side via the alternating-coface map, requires a routine $\op$-passage to apply the chain-complex statement to the cochain complex.
1355	
1356	\textbf{Note on Mathlib coverage.} Mathlib does not currently host a formalisation of the Koszul complex or of any Čech-to-derived-functor spectral sequence (Stacks tags 03OU, 01EW). The proof above bypasses both by working only with the augmented complex on each basic-open patch and the extra-degeneracy contraction --- the same route used in the standard pre-Koszul textbook proofs. The Čech-to-derived-functor comparison statement (i.e.\ the statement that, under the acyclicity established here, Čech cohomology agrees with the derived-functor cohomology) is a separate mathematical theorem whose formalisation is queued for a later iteration as a project-local construction, again as a direct "augmented Čech complex is a resolution of $\mathcal O_C(U)$" argument rather than a full spectral sequence.
1357	
1358	\begin{remark}[Finite-subspanning reduction]\label{rem:basic_open_cech_finite_subspanning}
1359	  Although the hypothesis $\langle s\rangle = \mathcal O_C(U)$ does not restrict $s$ to be finite, the unit element $1 \in \mathcal O_C(U)$ is witnessed by a finite $\mathcal O_C(U)$-linear combination of elements of $s$. There exists therefore a finite subset $s_0 \subseteq s$ with $\langle s_0\rangle = \mathcal O_C(U)$. The two covers $\mathfrak U = \{D(f)\}_{f \in s}$ and $\mathfrak U_0 = \{D(f)\}_{f \in s_0}$ then satisfy $\bigsqcup_{f \in s} D(f) = U = \bigsqcup_{f \in s_0} D(f)$ (both spanning conditions yield $U$ itself), and the inclusion of index sets $s_0 \hookrightarrow s$ induces a refinement map of cochain complexes $C^\bullet(\mathfrak U, \mathcal O_C) \to C^\bullet(\mathfrak U_0, \mathcal O_C)$ obtained by precomposing each multi-index with the inclusion. Because both covers generate the same sieve on $U$, this refinement map is a quasi-isomorphism; it suffices therefore to prove acyclicity for $\mathfrak U_0$. After this reduction, every cochain factor at degree $n$ is a \emph{finite} product indexed by $s_0^{n+1}$, and the product-localisation commutation in Step~2 holds (Mathlib's \texttt{IsLocalizedModule.pi} requires a finite indexing set, so the reduction to $s_0$ is what makes the standard textbook argument formalisable).
1360	\end{remark}
1361	
