\section{\v{C}ech acyclicity and vanishing on affines}
\label{sec:cech_acyclicity}

This section builds the instance-driven pipeline that converts Čech acyclicity of a cover into the vanishing of $H^{\prime n}(U, \mathcal F)$ on affine opens. The engine is the extra-degeneracy contraction for basic-open covers, developed in Sections~\ref{sec:basic_open_infrastructure}--\ref{sec:basic_open_acyclicity}.

\subsection{Top-supremum transport}

When a cover $\mathfrak U$ is Čech-acyclic and its supremum is the whole space, the vanishing of Čech cohomology transports to the vanishing of whole-space cohomology.

\begin{theorem}[Top-supremum transport, abstract sheaf form]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_supr_of_isCechAcyclicCover, def:Scheme_HModule_eq_HModule_prime_linearEquiv, def:Scheme_HModule, def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
  Let $\mathfrak U$ be a Čech-acyclic cover with $\bigsqcup_i \mathfrak U_i = \top$, and assume a comparison isomorphism between Čech and derived cohomology. For $n \ge 1$, the type $H^{n}(X, \mathcal F)$ is a subsingleton.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  The Čech-acyclic consumer gives a subsingleton on $H^{\prime n}(\bigsqcup \mathfrak U_i, \mathcal F)$. Rewrite the supremum to $\top$ using the cover hypothesis, then transport across the whole-space bridge.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Top-supremum transport, curve form]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top_curve}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top_curve}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  Same statement at $\mathcal F = \mathcal O_C$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Direct specialisation.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Comparison-iso typeclass carrier}

To avoid threading an explicit comparison isomorphism through every call site, we package it as a typeclass.

\begin{definition}[Comparison-iso carrier]
  \label{def:Scheme_HasCechToHModuleIso}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HasCechToHModuleIso}
  \uses{def:Scheme_cechCohomology, def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
  Let $\mathfrak U$ be an indexed open cover. The typeclass $\HasCechToHModuleIso$ asserts the existence of a $k$-linear comparison isomorphism between Čech cohomology and $H'$ cohomology of the supremum, in every degree.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Comparison-iso extractor]
  \label{def:Scheme_cechToHModuleIso}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cechToHModuleIso}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HasCechToHModuleIso}
  Given an instance of $\HasCechToHModuleIso$, the extractor returns the comparison isomorphism by choice.
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}[Instance-driven top-supremum transport, abstract sheaf form]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_hasCechToHModuleIso_top}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule_of_hasCechToHModuleIso_top}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top, def:Scheme_HasCechToHModuleIso, def:Scheme_cechToHModuleIso}
  Under Čech-acyclicity, $\HasCechToHModuleIso$, and $\bigsqcup \mathfrak U_i = \top$, the type $H^{n}(X, \mathcal F)$ is a subsingleton for $n \ge 1$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Apply the explicit top-supremum theorem with the extractor supplying the comparison isomorphism.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Instance-driven top-supremum transport, curve form]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_hasCechToHModuleIso_top_curve}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule_of_hasCechToHModuleIso_top_curve}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_hasCechToHModuleIso_top, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  Same statement at $\mathcal F = \mathcal O_C$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Direct specialisation.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Instance-driven supremum transport for $H'$, abstract sheaf form]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_supr_of_hasCechToHModuleIso}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule'_supr_of_hasCechToHModuleIso}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_supr_of_isCechAcyclicCover, def:Scheme_HasCechToHModuleIso, def:Scheme_cechToHModuleIso}
  Under Čech-acyclicity and $\HasCechToHModuleIso$, the type $H^{\prime n}(\bigsqcup \mathfrak U_i, \mathcal F)$ is a subsingleton for $n \ge 1$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Apply the explicit supremum consumer with the extractor supplying the comparison isomorphism.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Instance-driven supremum transport for $H'$, curve form]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_supr_of_hasCechToHModuleIso_curve}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule'_supr_of_hasCechToHModuleIso_curve}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_supr_of_hasCechToHModuleIso, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  Same statement at $\mathcal F = \mathcal O_C$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Direct specialisation.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Generalised rewrite-bridge, abstract sheaf form]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_of_hasCechToHModuleIso}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule'_of_hasCechToHModuleIso}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_supr_of_hasCechToHModuleIso}
  Under Čech-acyclicity and $\HasCechToHModuleIso$, if $\bigsqcup \mathfrak U_i = U$, then $H^{\prime n}(U, \mathcal F)$ is a subsingleton for $n \ge 1$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Rewrite the supremum to $U$ and apply the previous theorem.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Generalised rewrite-bridge, curve form]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_of_hasCechToHModuleIso_curve}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule'_of_hasCechToHModuleIso_curve}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_of_hasCechToHModuleIso, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  Same statement at $\mathcal F = \mathcal O_C$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Direct specialisation.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Affine Čech-acyclic cover carrier}

The predicate $\IsAffineHModuleVanishing$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_IsAffineHModuleVanishing}) requires vanishing on every affine open. To instantiate it from Čech data, we introduce a carrier class that bundles the existence of a suitable cover per affine open.

\begin{definition}[Affine Čech-acyclic cover carrier]
  \label{def:Scheme_HasAffineCechAcyclicCover}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HasAffineCechAcyclicCover}
  \uses{def:Scheme_IsCechAcyclicCover, def:Scheme_HasCechToHModuleIso}
  For every affine open $U$, there exists an indexed cover $\mathfrak U$ with $\bigsqcup \mathfrak U_i = U$ that is Čech-acyclic and carries a comparison isomorphism.
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}[Producer for $\IsAffineHModuleVanishing$]
  \label{thm:Scheme_instIsAffineHModuleVanishing_of_hasAffineCechAcyclicCover}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.instIsAffineHModuleVanishing_of_hasAffineCechAcyclicCover}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HasAffineCechAcyclicCover, thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_of_hasCechToHModuleIso}
  If $\HasAffineCechAcyclicCover$ holds, then $\IsAffineHModuleVanishing$ holds.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Per affine $U$, extract the cover from the carrier, register the acyclicity and comparison instances, and apply the rewrite-bridge.
\end{proof}

\section{Basic-open cover infrastructure}
\label{sec:basic_open_infrastructure}

This section packages the standard basic-open cover of an affine open into the project's conventions. Given a subset $s \subseteq \mathcal O_X(U)$ spanning the unit ideal, the basic opens $D(f)$ for $f \in s$ form a cover of $U$. All members and their finite intersections are again affine.

\begin{definition}[Basic-open cover]
  \label{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover}
  Let $U$ be an open of $X$ and $s \subseteq \mathcal O_X(U)$. The basic-open cover indexed by $s$ sends $f \in s$ to $D(f)$.
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}[Supremum equality]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_supr_of_span_eq_top}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_supr_of_span_eq_top}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover}
  If $U$ is affine and $s$ spans the unit ideal, then $\bigsqcup_{f \in s} D(f) = U$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Standard characterisation: the union of basic opens equals the whole affine if and only if the generators span the unit ideal.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Affine membership]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_isAffineOpen}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_isAffineOpen}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover}
  If $U$ is affine, then every member $D(f)$ of the basic-open cover is affine.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  The basic open of an affine scheme is affine.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Existence producer from basic-open evidence]
  \label{thm:Scheme_hasAffineCechAcyclicCover_of_basicOpen}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.hasAffineCechAcyclicCover_of_basicOpen}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HasAffineCechAcyclicCover, def:Scheme_basicOpenCover, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_supr_of_span_eq_top}
  If for every affine open $U$ there exists a spanning subset $s \subseteq \mathcal O_X(U)$ such that the basic-open cover by $s$ is Čech-acyclic and carries a comparison isomorphism, then $\HasAffineCechAcyclicCover$ holds.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Bundle the basic-open cover together with the supremum equality into the existential shape required by the carrier.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Curve specialisation]
  \label{thm:Scheme_hasAffineCechAcyclicCover_of_basicOpen_curve}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.hasAffineCechAcyclicCover_of_basicOpen_curve}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_hasAffineCechAcyclicCover_of_basicOpen}
  Same statement specialised to the structure sheaf $\mathcal O_C$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Direct application.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Intersection helpers}

Finite intersections of basic opens are again basic opens of a product.

\begin{theorem}[Pairwise intersection]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_inter_eq_basicOpen_mul}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_inter_eq_basicOpen_mul}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover}
  For $f, g \in s$, $D(f) \cap D(g) = D(fg)$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Standard identity for basic opens.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Pairwise intersection is affine]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_inter_isAffineOpen}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_inter_isAffineOpen}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_inter_eq_basicOpen_mul}
  If $U$ is affine, then $D(f) \cap D(g)$ is affine.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  By the previous theorem it is a single basic open.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[$n$-ary intersection]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_eq_basicOpen_prod}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_finset_inf'_eq_basicOpen_prod}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover}
  For a non-empty finite subset $t \subseteq s$,
  \[
    \bigcap_{f \in t} D(f) \;=\; D\Bigl(\prod_{f \in t} f\Bigr).
  \]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  By induction on the finite subset, using the binary case.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[$n$-ary intersection is affine]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_isAffineOpen}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_finset_inf'_isAffineOpen}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_eq_basicOpen_prod}
  If $U$ is affine, then $\bigcap_{f \in t} D(f)$ is affine.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  By the previous theorem it is a single basic open.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[$n$-ary intersection inclusion]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_le}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_finset_inf'_le}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_eq_basicOpen_prod}
  For a non-empty finite subset $t \subseteq s$, $\bigcap_{f \in t} D(f) \subseteq U$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  A basic open is contained in the ambient affine.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[$n$-ary intersection as a localization]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_isLocalization}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_finset_inf'_isLocalization}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_eq_basicOpen_prod, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_le}
  Let $U$ be affine and $t$ a non-empty finite subset of $s$, and write $V = \bigcap_{f \in t} D(f)$ and $g = \prod_{f \in t} f$. Then $\mathcal O_X(V)$ is the localization of $\mathcal O_X(U)$ away from $g$, with the algebra structure given by the presheaf restriction map.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  Apply the standard localization theorem for basic opens, using the equality and inclusion theorems above.
\end{proof}

\section{Čech acyclicity for the structure sheaf on affine basic-open covers}
\label{sec:basic_open_acyclicity}

Let $X$ be a $k$-scheme, $U \subseteq X$ an affine open, and $s \subseteq \mathcal O_X(U)$ a set generating the unit ideal. Write $\mathfrak U = \{D(f)\}_{f \in s}$ for the basic-open cover. The Čech cochain complex of the structure sheaf with respect to $\mathfrak U$ is
\[
  C^n(\mathfrak U, \mathcal O_X) \;=\; \prod_{(f_0,\dots,f_n) \in s^{n+1}} \mathcal O_X\bigl(D(f_0) \cap \cdots \cap D(f_n)\bigr),
\]
with the standard alternating-coface differential.

\begin{theorem}[Čech acyclicity for the structure sheaf]
  \label{thm:basicOpenCover_isCechAcyclicCover_toModuleKSheaf}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_isCechAcyclicCover_toModuleKSheaf}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover, def:Scheme_IsCechAcyclicCover, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_eq_basicOpen_prod, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_le, thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_isLocalization}
  The Čech cohomology $\check H^n(\mathfrak U, \mathcal O_X)$ vanishes for every $n \ge 1$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_isLocalization, def:Scheme_IsCechAcyclicCover}
  The classical proof proceeds in four steps.

  \textbf{Step~1: Reduction to per-generator local exactness.} Since $s$ generates the unit ideal, exactness of a map of $\mathcal O_X(U)$-modules is a local property at the cover $\{D(f)\}_{f \in s}$. It suffices to prove exactness after localizing at each generator $f \in s$.

  \textbf{Step~2: Identification of the localized complex.} Localizing at $f$ identifies the factor at $(f_0,\dots,f_n)$ with $\mathcal O_X(U)[1/(f f_0 \cdots f_n)]$. Reassembling, the localized Čech complex is naturally isomorphic to the Čech complex of $D(f)$ with respect to the restricted cover $\{D(f) \cap D(f')\}_{f' \in s}$.

  \textbf{Step~3: Contraction by extra degeneracy.} In the cover of $D(f)$, the member indexed by $f' = f$ is $D(f)$ itself. The augmented Čech complex therefore admits a section: map a family to its component at $f$. This section extends to an extra degeneracy on the augmented simplicial object, exhibiting the augmented Čech complex as contractible. Consequently the complex is exact in all positive degrees.

  \textbf{Step~4: Globalization.} Each localized differential is exact, so the unlocalized differential is exact by the local-to-global principle for spanning sets. Hence $\check H^n(\mathfrak U, \mathcal O_X) = 0$ for $n \ge 1$.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[Finite-subspanning reduction]
  \label{rem:basic_open_cech_finite_subspanning}
  Although $s$ need not be finite, the unit ideal condition guarantees a finite subset $s_0 \subseteq s$ already generating the unit ideal. The two covers indexed by $s$ and $s_0$ induce the same sieve on $U$, so the refinement map is a quasi-isomorphism. It therefore suffices to prove acyclicity for a finite cover, which makes every cochain factor a finite product.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Lean implementation]
  The proof uses the local-to-global exactness theorem for spanning sets, the structure-sheaf-section-as-localization theorem for affine basic opens, exactness preservation under localization, and the extra-degeneracy contraction theorem for augmented simplicial objects. Mathlib does not currently host a formalisation of the Koszul complex or of the Čech-to-derived-functor spectral sequence; the proof above bypasses both by working directly with the augmented complex on each basic-open patch.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Use in the project}

The chain built in this chapter composes as follows. Čech acyclicity for the structure sheaf on basic-open covers yields the Čech-acyclic hypothesis. The comparison isomorphism between Čech and derived cohomology (a project-local construction, queued for a subsequent iteration) yields the $\HasCechToHModuleIso$ hypothesis. The existence producer of Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_hasAffineCechAcyclicCover_of_basicOpen} then assembles these into $\HasAffineCechAcyclicCover$, which the producer of Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_instIsAffineHModuleVanishing_of_hasAffineCechAcyclicCover} converts into $\IsAffineHModuleVanishing$. Together with the $H^0$ finiteness ladder of Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafModuleK}, this closes Phase~A step~6 and delivers the genus carrier $\Module.\Finite\,k\,H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$.

\end{chapter}

